description:
File: rust/lichen-gateway/src/gateway.rs
Lines: 40-43

The mesh_to_upstream() function uses a fixed 1500-byte buffer for SCHC decompression. While this matches standard Ethernet MTU, it could truncate packets if the SCHC codec supports larger outputs or if the mesh uses a different MTU.

Current code:
```rust
pub fn mesh_to_upstream(&mut self, l2_payload: &[u8]) -> Option<Vec<u8>> {
    // ...
    let mut out = vec![0u8; 1500];
    match decompress(l2_payload_body(l2_payload), &mut out) {
        Ok(n) => {
            out.truncate(n);
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```

The issue is that the code doesn't check if decompress() wanted to write more than 1500 bytes. Depending on how the SCHC codec signals buffer-too-small errors, this could either:
1. Return an error (safe, but undocumented)
2. Silently truncate (data corruption)
3. Panic (crash)

Impact: Potential data truncation or undefined behavior for oversized packets.

Fix: Make the buffer size configurable or check SchcError for buffer overflow:
```rust
// Either use a larger buffer with configurable max:
let mut out = vec![0u8; self.config.max_ipv6_packet_size.unwrap_or(1500)];

// Or document the assumption:
/// Note: Output is limited to 1500 bytes (standard Ethernet MTU).
/// SCHC codec will return an error for larger packets.
```

Tags: correctness, schc, gateway
